    <div class="rightSection" id="precautions">
        <p1>
            <h2>Precautions</h2>
            &#9657; <u>All</u> operators must be wearing gloves.
            <br> &#9657; <u>All</u> benches must have scratch protection in the form of either pink foam or the ESD mat.
            <br> &#9657; <u>All</u> operators must follow one piece flow, meaning there is only one repair order on the bench at a time. In verification, you are the last operator to handle the order before shipment, and you are performing the final quality
            check.
            <br> &#9657; <u>All</u> test equipment including AC adapters, USB cables must be checked daily for damage. Any damaged or dysfunctional test equipment must be reported to a supervisor or team lead.<br>
            <div style="color:red"><u><b>There are no exceptions to these rules. If there is a preventative, inform a lead or supervisor immediately.</b></u></div>
        </p1>
    </div>

    <div class="rightSection" id="dataentry">
        <p1>
            <h2>Data Entry</h2>
            Verification is performed primarily using the <a href="galaxyprd.unitedradio.com/VerificationNew"> Verification page.</a>
            <br>The Verification process is fast, repetitive, and follows a very specific routine. There are no work orders or travelers to read or fill out when performing the Verification process. This is done intentionally, so that your answers are
            compared to information in the database to ensure that process errors will not result in us shipping incorrect items to consumers with incorrect information. The page will only prompt for the information you need to enter. There are other
            questions on the page, but not all will require an answer every time.
            <br>Each RO on the box must go through the entire verification process individually. If there are multiple ROs in a box, you must complete verification for every RO in the box before moving on.
            <br>Begin by scanning one of the ROs on the box into the "RO Number" box. Press Enter or click "Look Up RO#" to proceed.
            <br>The cursor moves to the next question you must answer. The next step will be to enter the first 4 characters of the consumer's address. This is found on the top of the box on the shipping label. Press Enter or Tab, or click out of the
            entry field to proceed.
            <br>Next, scan the tracking number on the box. Be sure not to confuse this with the smaller barcode on the label, which is not used at our facility. The cursor will automatically proceed to the next question.
            <br>You will see that the cursor moves all the way down to the bottom, and a number of buttons appear. Each button corresponds to an accessory in the box. All of the common HAC accessories and joycons are listed here, but most game cards are
            not. There is a reference sheet of component numbers available at every bench. For each individual JoyCon RO, you will select only 1 JoyCon. For boxes with 2 Joycons, the left-side RO label should correspond to the left side JoyCon, and the
            right-side RO label should correspond to the right side JoyCon.
            <br>If an item is not listed here, you may search for it by entering a keyword in the entry box and clicking "Search Component". If you know the component number, such as one listed on the supplementary sheet, you may enter it in the same
            box and click "Add Component" instead of "Search Component". Any item which does not have a part number should be entered as Miscellaneous, which has a button of its' own. If you are not sure whether or not an item should have a unique component
            number, don't hesitate to ask an experienced peer, team lead, or supervisor.
            <br> When you have added the correct JoyCon part number, click "Verify Components".
            <br> Provided you have chosen the correct corresponding component, and there is no underlying failure, the form will proceed to the next field.
            <br> Next, enter your initials.
            <br> After your initials are entered, a button at the bottom of the form will appear that is labeled "Complete Verification". Click this button to complete the form. A popup message will confirm this, and another button will appear.
            <br> The next button that appears is labeled "Ready to Ship". Clicking this button will result in a short processing delay, followed by a popup message confirming the tranmission was successful. If you receive an error, this may be something
            to bring to the attention of your team lead or supervisor.
            <br> If a message appears that states "Invalid RO status transition from Ready to Ship to Ready to Ship", this is not a legitimate error. It is likely caused by double-clicking the button quickly, and may be ignored.
            <br> After "Ready to Ship" has been successfully sent, a button labeled "Shipped" will appear. Again, click the button and await the "Success" popup. If an error appears at this stage, it is likely legitimate and needs to be processed as a
            discrepancy.
            <br> After "Shipped" is successfully sent, the verification process is completed. If you neglect to click all three of the buttons (verification complete, ready to ship, shipped), the order will not be closed and it will be as though the work
            was not performed. Be sure to always remember to click each button before moving on to the next RO. If you neglect to click these buttons, it would be as though the work was never performed.
            <br> If each RO in a box has been completed, we must prepare the order for shipment.
        </p1>
